Here are guidelines for creating a flowchart for your capstone project (system-based, covering mobile, web and desktop apps) — based on standard flowchart symbol conventions from SmartDraw. 
SmartDraw

You can adapt these to your specific system, modules and deployment platforms.

1. Define the scope & purpose

Clarify what part of the system your flowchart will cover. For example:

User login / authentication flow

Main menu/navigation across mobile/web/desktop

Data input, processing and output workflow

Error handling & exceptions

Decide the audience: Are you drawing this for developers, testers, stakeholders, or as documentation?

Identify the entry point and exit point of the workflow (what starts the process and what ends it).

2. Choose the correct symbols

According to SmartDraw:

6

Here are the basic ones you’ll want to use:

Start/End (Terminator symbol) – usually an oval or “pill” shape. Marks start or end of the workflow. 
SmartDraw

Process / Action (Rectangle) – represents a step or action (e.g., “Validate user credentials”). 
SmartDraw

Decision (Diamond) – a branching point (e.g., “Is password correct?”) with yes/no or multiple outcomes. 
SmartDraw

Input/Output (Parallelogram) – data entering or leaving the system (e.g., user input, report output). 
SmartDraw

Data Storage / Database (Cylinder or special symbol) – indicates persistent data storage (e.g., “Save session token”). 
SmartDraw

Connector / Off-page (circle/arrow symbol) – for flows that continue elsewhere or across pages. 
SmartDraw

Tip: If you use less common symbols, include a legend to ensure clarity. 
SmartDraw

3. Map out the high-level flow first

Sketch the major steps in your system across the three platforms (mobile, web, desktop). For example:

Start → User chooses platform (mobile/web/desktop)

Show login / authentication flow

After login → Show main module(s) (e.g., Dashboard, Data Entry, Reporting)

Data processing & storage steps

Output/Report generation or logout → End

At this high level you’re not worrying yet about every detail — just the main path(s).

4. Drill into module-specific flows

For each major module or platform, create more detailed flows. You can structure by platform or by function.
For example:

Mobile app: Launch → Check network → Show login screen → If first time → show onboarding → else → main dashboard → user taps “Add Record” → enter data → submit → API call → store in database → show confirmation → end.

Web app: Browser opens → Load landing page → user logs in → choose module → data export → download file → end.

Desktop app: Start application → connect to local database → synchronize with server → user edits offline → sync when online → end.

Use decision diamonds for branching logic (e.g., “Is user online?”). Use input/output shape for “Enter data” or “Download file”. Use data-storage symbol for “Save to server” or “Local DB”.

5. Pay attention to cross-platform aspects

Since your system spans mobile, web and desktop, your flowchart should reflect shared logic and platform-specific logic.

Show where the flows converge: e.g., all platforms call the same API, or all update the same database.

Use consistent notation so the reader can easily follow differences vs similarities.

Optionally use swimlanes (horizontal/vertical lanes) labelled by platform (Mobile / Web / Desktop) to visually distinguish which steps belong to which platform. (Although SmartDraw notes you can stick to basic symbols unless you’re doing very detailed diagrams.) 
SmartDraw

6. Use clear arrows and flow direction

Ensure arrows clearly show the direction of flow (typically top to bottom, left to right).

Avoid crossing arrows where possible. If necessary, use connector symbols.

Label decision out-going arrows (e.g., “Yes”, “No”) for clarity.

Make sure every process step leads to a next step (except end), and decision steps have every branch accounted for (i.e., no “dead” un‐handled path).

7. Keep it readable and manageable

Don’t overcrowd one flowchart with every tiny detail — break into sub‐ flowcharts if needed (you can use subroutine symbol for “See detailed flowchart”). 
SmartDraw

Use whitespace, align symbols, and maintain consistent symbol sizes.

Use descriptive labels inside symbols (e.g., “Validate Credentials” rather than “Step 1”).

Add a title, legend (if you use many symbol types), date and version of the flowchart.

8. Review & validate with stakeholders

Walk through the flowchart step‐by‐step with team members (developers, testers, business analysts) to ensure accuracy.

Check whether all platforms (mobile, web, desktop) are covered, and whether the branching logic is correct.

Verify that storage/data flows, error cases and exit paths are included.

Update the flowchart if changes happen in system design.

9. Document and integrate into your capstone deliverables

Include the flowchart in your requirements/design document or appendix.

Provide a short narrative describing the flow (so someone reading the chart knows what platform/option is being followed).

Highlight any platform‐specific differences (e.g., offline mode for desktop, push notifications for mobile).

Use the flowchart to guide test cases and verification.

10. Example small snippet

Here’s a textual example for the login process across platforms:

Start (Oval) → Show “Platform Selection” (Rectangle) → Decision: “Is Platform Mobile?” (Diamond)

Yes → Show Mobile Login Screen (Rectangle) → Input: “Enter credentials” (Parallelogram) → Process: “Validate credentials via API” (Rectangle) → Decision: “Credentials valid?” (Diamond)

Yes → Process: “Initialize mobile session” (Rectangle) → End (Oval)

No → Process: “Show error message” (Rectangle) → End (Oval)

No → Decision: “Is Platform Web?” (Diamond) … and so on for desktop.

You would draw this using the appropriate symbols for each step.